I think it works if you use the `Dispatcher` to remove the items. That way you can wait for Avalonia to commit the changes before removing the item. I've used the following item view model for my tests: 

```cs
public sealed class Item : ViewModelBase
{
    private string _value;

    // Added two private fields which we need to access later. 
    private MainWindowViewModel owner;
    private bool _init;
    
    public Item(MainWindowViewModel owner, string value)
    {
        this.owner = owner;
        _value = value;
        
        this.WhenAnyValue(x => x.Value)
            .Subscribe(_ => RemoveMe());

        // RxUI is calling WhenAnyValue in the constructor for some reason. We don't want this, so we wait for the model to be ready
        _init = true;
    }

    
    // I made a function of it. Feel free to move it to your lambda if you want to.
    private void RemoveMe()
    {
        if (!_init) return;
        Dispatcher.UIThread.Post(() => owner.Items.Remove(this));
    }
    
    public string Value
    {
        get => _value;
        set => this.RaiseAndSetIfChanged(ref _value, value);
    }
}
```

tbh I don't consider this a bug. Therefore I move this into a discussion. If you are okay with the solution showed above, please mark it as the answer for others.

I think the better way would be using `IsLoading` state that keeps information about all possible options.
Then you can check it for a specific object in `CanExecute`.
Some pseudo-code to show the idea:

```
DownloadUpdatePlayButton = new RelayCommand(StartDownloading, p => !IsLoading[p]);
```

and inside of your `StartDownloading`:

```csharp
StartDownloading(int id)
{
    IsLoading[id] = true;
    // process
    IsLoading[id] = false;
} 
```

`id` is passed via `CommandParameter`.

