@danwalmsley Yes. In my case, "can" execute is for whether the action makes contextual sense and "may" execute is whether the action is allowed. For example, the RelayCommand/DelegateCommand/whatever would have an overloaded constructor that takes a third argument of type `Func<bool>`. I think Avalonia uses implicit command definitions, but the same concept would apply.

Here is a snippet to illustrate:
```
public void DeleteItem(object parameter) {
    foreach (var item in (IEnumerable<Item>)parameter)
        _repo.DeleteItem(item);
}
public bool CanDeleteItem(object parameter) {
    return (parameter as IEnumerable<Item>)?.Count > 0 ?? false;
}
public bool MayDeleteItem() {
    return _permissionManager.HasDeleteItemPermission();
}
```

